This project is a precision oncology platform designed to analyze cancer genomic data and provide personalized therapy recommendations based on clinically relevant variants. The system accepts either raw Variant Call Format (VCF) files from whole-exome sequencing or pre-annotated VCF files generated using the Ensembl Variant Effect Predictor (VEP). When a raw VCF file is uploaded, an automated backend bash pipeline performs variant annotation using VEP to extract gene symbols, HGVS protein changes, functional consequences, population allele frequencies, and other clinically relevant annotations. If the user uploads an already annotated VCF file, the annotation step is skipped to reduce processing time. In both cases, a Python-based filtering pipeline is then applied to identify clinically actionable variants by removing common population variants, retaining variants with high or moderate functional impact, focusing on canonical transcripts, and prioritizing known cancer driver genes. The pipeline also standardizes variant representations (e.g., HGVS protein format) to enable consistent matching with a curated oncology knowledge base compiled from sources such as OncoKB, COSMIC, and pharmacogenomics datasets. Additionally, tumor mutational burden (TMB) is calculated from filtered variants to provide an important immunotherapy biomarker. The final output presents prioritized actionable mutations, associated targeted therapies, supporting evidence levels, and biomarker insights, enabling a structured and interpretable framework for personalized cancer treatment decision support
